# 🕵️ Man-in-the-Middle (MITM) Attack

## 📌 What is a MITM Attack?
A Man-in-the-Middle (MITM) attack is a cyber attack where an attacker secretly intercepts and may alter communication between two parties without their knowledge.

---

## ⚙️ How it Works
1. User connects to a website or network  
2. Attacker positions themselves between user and server  
3. Communication passes through attacker  
4. Attacker can read or modify data  

---

## 💥 Impact / Damage
- Theft of login credentials  
- Data interception (banking, emails)  
- Session hijacking  
- Unauthorized access  

---

## 🛡️ Prevention / Protection
- Use **HTTPS websites (SSL/TLS)**  
- Avoid public/unsecured Wi-Fi  
- Use a **VPN**  
- Enable encryption  
- Use secure network configurations  

---

## 🧠 Key Concepts
- MITM = interception attack  
- Attacker acts as a “middle layer”  
- Communication appears normal  

---

## 🔗 Integration with IT Systems
- Network security protects communication  
- MFA reduces impact of stolen credentials  
- Monitoring detects unusual activity  

---

## 💼 Real-world Relevance
MITM attacks commonly occur on public Wi-Fi and can be used to steal sensitive information like passwords and banking data.

---

## 🔥 Important Line
A MITM attack intercepts communication between two parties to steal or manipulate data.

---

## 🧠 Simple Understanding
MITM = “attacker sitting in the middle of communication”

---

## 🎤 Interview Line
A Man-in-the-Middle attack occurs when an attacker intercepts communication between two parties to steal or modify data.
